      <hedline>
        <hl1>Working Family of One</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lisa Norment letter says it is hard for her to sympathize with working families struggling to live middle-class life (Sept 10 article) because she can only dream of middle-class life as single, childless person with yearly income between $20,000 and $30,000</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Working Families Strain to Live Middle-Class Life'' (front page, Sept. 10): As a member of the working class, I can only dream of a middle-class life. I am single and childless, and have a yearly income between $20,000 and $30,000.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Working Families Strain to Live Middle-Class Life'' (front page, Sept. 10): As a member of the working class, I can only dream of a middle-class life. I am single and childless, and have a yearly income between $20,000 and $30,000.</p>
        <p>I survive by frequenting thrift shops for bare necessities, like warm sweaters. I attend perhaps three movies a year and eat out twice a year at most.</p>
        <p>It is difficult to sympathize with those families you say stretch meager budgets to buy big-screen televisions, home decorations or lessons for the children when so many of us single, child-free, working-class people struggle to afford rent, electricity and winter coats. The most challenging position in America today is to be single, childless and middle income.</p>
        <p>LISA NORMENT  Briarwood, Queens, Sept. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
